[5] USA (Texas)
Date: Sun 3 Apr 2011
Source: Houston Chronicle [edited]
http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/metropolitan/7503980.html


Local public health officials are investigating a confirmed case of
measles in a baby, the 1st such case in Houston in years. The Houston
Area Health Alert Network sent an email on Friday [1 Apr 2011] noting
that an 11 month old child, who attended the Cirque du Soleil
performance at Sam Houston Race Park on 20 Mar 2011, developed fever
the next day and a rash 3 days later. She later tested positive for
the highly contagious virus. The email asked local health care
providers to consider measles in patients presenting with a rash.

The baby is recovering, according to Kathy Barton, spokeswoman for
the Houston health department. Barton said health officials are
aggressively investigating any contact the child may have had with
at-risk people but said the situation is nothing like it was in the
late 1980s and early 1990s, when the city's low child immunization
rate -- 11 per cent -- led to an outbreak that hospitalized a third of
confirmed cases. Houston's immunization rate is now 87 per cent.

Barton said the baby's household contacts are all immune. Measles,
best known for a red skin rash, is a potentially deadly virus
[disease] that spreads through contact with a sneezing, coughing,
infected person. Children 1st get vaccinated for it at 12 months. The
health alert network's email noted that there have been multiple
laboratory-confirmed cases of measles in various parts of the United
States in recent months, including Minnesota, Massachusetts, and
Florida. The local child is believed to have been exposed during a
trip to Orlando, Florida on 2-8 Mar 2011.

The last reported cases of measles in Houston were confirmed in 2005
and 2001. The cases were exposed to the virus on trips to Mexico and
China, respectively.

[byline: Tod Ackerman]

