[6] USA (overall)
Date: Thu 31 Mar 2011
Source: About.com Pediatrics [edited]
http://pediatrics.about.com/b/2011/03/31/measles-case-count-heading-for-a-measles-outbreak-record.htm


As many people know, measles cases continue to increase because of
the current measles outbreaks in various parts of the country. The
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention puts us at 35 total cases
for 2011, which now include 6 recent cases in Minnesota.

The only problem with that number is that the recent measles case
count in Minnesota is now at least 14, which means the United States
total is more like 44. In comparison, last year [2010], there were
only 4 reports of measles in the US by the beginning of April 2010. In
2009, the measles case count was also only 4 cases at this point in
the year. Even in 2008, a record year for measles in the US, with a
total of 140 measles cases for the year, there were only 7 cases by
the beginning of April 2008. If we are a third of the way to our
previous measles record in just the 13th week of the year, what does
that mean for the rest of the year?

Keep in mind that as the measles case counts get higher, the chances
of actually seeing children with serious side effects with measles
increases. Fortunately, the more serious measles complications, such
as seizures (0.6 per cent), encephalitis (0.1 per cent), and death
(0.2 per cent), are not very common. But even if only one in 1000
children with measles develops encephalitis, it isn't hard to
understand that as the measles case count approaches 500 or 1000, we
are going to be more likely to see a child with this complication.
Even without the updated numbers, CDC describes the current measles
case count as "beyond historical limits". Hopefully, we won't see just
how far beyond those limits we can reach this year [2011], and we can
move towards the goal of eliminating measles again.

[byline: Vincent Iannelli]

