[Interested readers should access the original text via the URL in
the heading to view the tabulated and graphical presentation of data
and the literature references cited in the text.

After a long period of success in reducing the incidence of measles
virus infection in the AFR, there has been a regrettable reversal of
success in the recent past in part due to the factors outlined above
and due to financial constraints.

During 2001/2008, reported measles-containing vaccine 1st dose (MCV1)
coverage increased from 55 per cent to 79 per cent in 46 African
countries, reported measles cases decreased by 93 per cent, and
estimated measles-related mortality decreased 91 per cent. By 2008, 40
of the 46 countries had established case-based surveillance in
accordance with WHO guidelines, and 28 reported measles incidence
under 5 cases per one million population per year.

In 2009, reported MCV1 coverage among the 46 African countries was 83
per cent; 12 (26 per cent) countries had measles incidence of under 5
cases per one million population in 2010, and 28 (61 per cent)
reported laboratory-confirmed measles outbreaks. Despite this
substantial progress toward reducing measles mortality and morbidity,
multiple outbreaks during 2009/2010 showed the gains were fragile, and
epidemiologic investigations of some outbreaks showed a failure to
vaccinate. The reasons for non-vaccination and corrective solutions
need to be determined, the quality of reported data should be
verified, and measles surveillance should be strengthened.

The African Region countries are: Algeria, Angola, Benin, Botswana,
Burkina Faso, Burundi, Cameroon, Cape Verde, Central African Republic,
Chad, Comoros, Congo, Cote d'Ivoire, Democratic Republic of Congo,
Equatorial Guinea, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Gabon, Gambia, Ghana, Guinea,
Guinea-Bissau, Kenya, Lesotho, Liberia, Madagascar, Malawi, Mali,
Mauritania, Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, Niger, Nigeria, Rwanda,
Sao Tome and Principe, Senegal, Seychelles, Sierra Leone, South
Africa, Swaziland, Togo, Uganda, United Republic of Tanzania, Zambia,
and Zimbabwe.

Many African governments are not allocating enough funds from their
annual budgets to health, says a study by WHO. Without additional
resources, vital health goals will not be achieved, it says.

In the 10 years since heads of state of African Union countries met
in Abuja, Nigeria and pledged to set a target of allocating "at least
15 per cent" of their annual budget to improve the health sector, only
Rwanda and South Africa have reached the objective, says WHO. -
Mod.CP]

******
[10] Spain (Sevilla)
Date: Fri 1 Apr 2011
Source: ABC de Sevilla [in Spanish trans. Mod.MPP, edited]
http://www.abcdesevilla.es/20110402/sevilla/sevi-salud-logra-aislar-brote-201104012148.html


Confirmed cases of measles continue to increase in Seville [Sevilla].
As of yesterday [31 Mar 2011], they have reached 432, 277 of whom are
directly related to the initial outbreak, while the rest are
considered sporadic cases. Given this finding, the Provincial Heath
Delegation has appealed to people to check on whether their
immunization schedules are up to date -- that is, that children have
received 2 doses of measles vaccine (at 15 months and 3 years), which
is presented as the MMR [measles, mumps and rubella] triple vaccine in
the childhood vaccination schedule.

They have also asked parents and guardians of children between 6 and
15 months of age in Sevilla, as well as the towns of Alcala de
Guadaira, Dos Hermanas, Mairena del Aljarafe and Tomares, to come to
their health centers so that their children receive measles vaccine.
This is an "exceptional and temporary measure for the duration of the
current situation," according to the Health Delegation.

The Provincial Health Delegation has stated that the only way to
prevent this disease is through vaccination. Measles remains a mild
disease, which occurs with a red skin rash and may include, among its
symptoms, otitis media, croup (laryngotracheobronchitis), pneumonia,
diarrhea, seizures, or febrile convulsions. That is why it is
recommended that all parents with children between 6 and 15 months [of
age] residing in the above mentioned localities should go to a health
center to receive the vaccine. For those who have been vaccinated at
younger than 12 months, they should receive a booster dose at 15
months [of age] and again at 3 years, according to the established
protocol. Those babies vaccinated between 12 and 15 months of age only
need to be revaccinated at 3 years of age.

This measure is intended to limit the spread of the virus presently
circulating widely in order to provide greater protection of the
infant population. It was emphasized that children under 6 months are
immunized naturally -- both from the mother during pregnancy and by
breastfeeding -- and, therefore, is not necessary to adopt vaccination
at this age.

The Health Delegation emphasised that the importance of vaccination
as a preventive measure is demonstrated by the fact that of the total
confirmed cases, "none of the victims had been previously
vaccinated."

[byline: J Spinola]

